{"title":"Where to Go Next for Recommender Systems? ID- vs. Modality-based Recommender Models Revisited","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Do modality-based recommender models (that encode item content such as text or images) truly rival or surpass traditional ID-based models in regular and warm-start item recommendation, beyond cold-start cases? Prior work lacked fair, apples-to-apples comparisons under identical backbones and settings.","method":"Perform a rigorous head-to-head study by replacing itemID embeddings with strong pre-trained modality encoders (BERT/RoBERTa for text; ResNet/Swin for images) and training end-to-end within identical recommender backbones (two-tower DSSM vs sequential SASRec) using the same loss, sampling, and hyperparameter protocol, with a DT-layer for dimension matching. Across three large-scale datasets (MIND text; HM and Bili images), results show that with the SASRec (seq2seq) backbone, MoRec matches or outperforms IDRec for text and is on par for vision even in warm-start settings, whereas with DSSM MoRec lags behind IDRec (e.g., Table 2, Table 3; lines 153–161, 169–180)."},{"problem":"Can recommender systems inherit advances from NLP and CV—i.e., do larger/stronger and pre-trained modality encoders translate into higher recommendation accuracy?","method":"Systematically vary modality encoders by size and strength and compare pre-trained vs training-from-scratch: BERT tiny/small/base, RoBERTa base, OPT, TextCNN, GloVe for text; ResNet18/34/50 and Swin-T/B for vision. Empirically, larger and stronger encoders generally yield higher HR/NDCG, and pre-trained encoders beat training-from-scratch, especially on smaller datasets and for vision (Figure 4; Table 4; lines 186–209). This establishes that MoRec can inherit progress from NLP/CV into RS."},{"problem":"Are modality representations from foundation models universal enough to be used as frozen features in RS, or is task-specific adaptation via end-to-end training necessary? What are the practical implications for efficiency and stability?","method":"Compare two-stage pipelines (pre-extract frozen modality features fed to the recommender, with/without additional MLP layers) against end-to-end fine-tuning of the modality encoder jointly with the RS backbone. Two-stage underperforms markedly—especially for image recommendation—while E2E delivers substantially better accuracy (Table 5; lines 215–221). The study also surfaces key practical challenges for E2E MoRec: far higher training cost than IDRec (often >100× compute/time; Table 6; lines 227–258) and training instability (model collapse) without carefully set learning rates for modality vs other modules (Figure 5; lines 277–299)."}]}
